WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.049 --> 00:00:07.520
WILLIAM FLOYD: Please, join
me in giving a warm welcome

00:00:07.520 --> 00:00:10.430
to Bonita Stewart
and DeRay McKesson.

00:00:10.430 --> 00:00:13.818
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:22.060 --> 00:00:24.640
BONITA STEWART: [INAUDIBLE].

00:00:24.640 --> 00:00:27.720
Well, thank you, William,
for just the introduction

00:00:27.720 --> 00:00:31.880
to this very special talk
that we have this afternoon.

00:00:31.880 --> 00:00:36.480
I am personally excited
to sit next to DeRay

00:00:36.480 --> 00:00:41.300
because he's just had such an
impact in one way or another

00:00:41.300 --> 00:00:43.270
in all of our lives.

00:00:43.270 --> 00:00:44.580
So DeRay, let's just start--

00:00:44.580 --> 00:00:48.330
you've had an incredible
personal journey.

00:00:48.330 --> 00:00:51.850
You follow things that
you're most passionate about.

00:00:51.850 --> 00:00:56.790
So I saw where you actually were
in the public school system,

00:00:56.790 --> 00:00:59.550
human resources official there.

00:00:59.550 --> 00:01:02.880
But tell us about
your personal journey.

00:01:02.880 --> 00:01:05.501
And we talked about
being born in Baltimore

00:01:05.501 --> 00:01:06.750
or spending time in Minnesota.

00:01:06.750 --> 00:01:10.140
But how did you follow
all of these passions?

00:01:10.140 --> 00:01:13.255
How did you set
out on this path?

00:01:13.255 --> 00:01:14.880
DERAY MCKESSON: So
I'll start by saying

00:01:14.880 --> 00:01:15.940
it's an honor to be here.

00:01:15.940 --> 00:01:16.420
It's great to be here.

00:01:16.420 --> 00:01:18.330
It's always a joy to
talk about this work.

00:01:18.330 --> 00:01:19.560
I do wish though
that we didn't have

00:01:19.560 --> 00:01:21.870
to spend so much time fighting
systems and structures that

00:01:21.870 --> 00:01:24.120
were killing us so we could
go do the cool things that

00:01:24.120 --> 00:01:26.410
make us joyous about the world.

00:01:26.410 --> 00:01:28.450
So I'm mindful of that.

00:01:28.450 --> 00:01:29.520
I think about this.

00:01:29.520 --> 00:01:32.100
I was in student government
my whole childhood,

00:01:32.100 --> 00:01:33.600
and that was really
important to me.

00:01:33.600 --> 00:01:35.349
Both of my parents
were addicted to drugs.

00:01:35.349 --> 00:01:37.440
My mother left when I was
three and she came back

00:01:37.440 --> 00:01:38.230
when I was 30.

00:01:38.230 --> 00:01:40.320
I just turned 33--
this is my Jesus year.

00:01:40.320 --> 00:01:41.634
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:41.634 --> 00:01:42.499
WILLIAM FLOYD: Amen.

00:01:42.499 --> 00:01:44.040
DERAY MCKESSON: My
mother left, yeah.

00:01:44.040 --> 00:01:47.400
So she just came back a couple
of years ago-- three years ago.

00:01:47.400 --> 00:01:50.562
And my father got clean when
I was around three or four.

00:01:50.562 --> 00:01:52.520
And I think about that
because in so many ways,

00:01:52.520 --> 00:01:54.357
I grew up in a
community of recovery.

00:01:54.357 --> 00:01:56.190
I grew up seeing people
put their lives back

00:01:56.190 --> 00:01:58.200
together in ways that
they didn't always think

00:01:58.200 --> 00:01:58.960
was possible.

00:01:58.960 --> 00:02:00.850
And that was childhood for me.

00:02:00.850 --> 00:02:03.754
I'll never forget coming
down from my bedroom one day

00:02:03.754 --> 00:02:05.420
and I see this guy
sitting on the couch.

00:02:05.420 --> 00:02:07.200
And I'm like, he
looks really familiar.

00:02:07.200 --> 00:02:08.550
And it was one of
my sister's friends.

00:02:08.550 --> 00:02:10.410
And I'm like, why is he in
our house in the morning--

00:02:10.410 --> 00:02:11.620
why is he on the couch?

00:02:11.620 --> 00:02:14.220
And he was recovering and
my father was counseling him

00:02:14.220 --> 00:02:15.550
during recovery.

00:02:15.550 --> 00:02:17.820
I have so many memories of that.

00:02:17.820 --> 00:02:19.420
And I think about
that all the time,

00:02:19.420 --> 00:02:21.682
because I know what it's
like to see communities

00:02:21.682 --> 00:02:22.890
break and come back together.

00:02:22.890 --> 00:02:25.230
And I think about this
work and resistance

00:02:25.230 --> 00:02:27.450
is seeing things break
and believing that they

00:02:27.450 --> 00:02:29.186
can come back together.

00:02:29.186 --> 00:02:30.810
But I taught, and
teaching was probably

00:02:30.810 --> 00:02:33.750
the single coolest,
most important,

00:02:33.750 --> 00:02:35.127
magical thing I've ever done.

00:02:35.127 --> 00:02:37.710
I taught sixth grade math here
in the East New York, Brooklyn.

00:02:37.710 --> 00:02:39.145
And sixth grade is beautiful.

00:02:39.145 --> 00:02:40.770
Seventh grade is
puberty and deodorant,

00:02:40.770 --> 00:02:42.323
but sixth grade is still--

00:02:42.323 --> 00:02:43.230
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:43.230 --> 00:02:44.100
--a lot of magic.

00:02:44.100 --> 00:02:45.750
If you've never been
in a group of kids

00:02:45.750 --> 00:02:47.208
who don't know they
need deodorant,

00:02:47.208 --> 00:02:49.320
that is seventh grade.

00:02:49.320 --> 00:02:51.930
Sixth grade is a lot of joy.

00:02:51.930 --> 00:02:57.420
And I'll never forget,
one day I was--

00:02:57.420 --> 00:02:59.800
I taught 69 in 120
minute classes,

00:02:59.800 --> 00:03:02.490
which is a long time for a
11-year-old to do anything, let

00:03:02.490 --> 00:03:03.660
alone math.

00:03:03.660 --> 00:03:05.987
And they were like,
can we go to gym early?

00:03:05.987 --> 00:03:08.070
And I'm like, absolutely,
you can go to gym early.

00:03:08.070 --> 00:03:09.600
I'm tired of you,
you're tired of me.

00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:10.820
We've been together
for a long time.

00:03:10.820 --> 00:03:12.861
First, second, third,
fifth, and seventh period--

00:03:12.861 --> 00:03:13.800
this one class.

00:03:13.800 --> 00:03:14.540
So I let them go.

00:03:14.540 --> 00:03:15.930
And they come back
really quickly

00:03:15.930 --> 00:03:19.340
and they're back
in my classroom.

00:03:19.340 --> 00:03:20.939
I'm like, why are
you back so quick?

00:03:20.939 --> 00:03:23.230
And I realize that they're
in love with the idea of gym

00:03:23.230 --> 00:03:25.267
more than the work of gym.

00:03:25.267 --> 00:03:27.100
And I say that because
in moments like this,

00:03:27.100 --> 00:03:29.558
I think people are more in love
with the idea of resistance

00:03:29.558 --> 00:03:30.900
than the work of resistance.

00:03:30.900 --> 00:03:32.290
And the question for me now--

00:03:32.290 --> 00:03:35.200
four years after we were in the
streets initially in Ferguson,

00:03:35.200 --> 00:03:37.189
it's like, what does
the work look like?

00:03:37.189 --> 00:03:39.730
How do we use spaces like this--
if we ever are going to just

00:03:39.730 --> 00:03:40.960
keep talking about it--

00:03:40.960 --> 00:03:43.720
to actually force people to
engage in the work and not just

00:03:43.720 --> 00:03:45.550
the conversation
of these things?

00:03:45.550 --> 00:03:47.530
So I got into it because
my friend got killed.

00:03:47.530 --> 00:03:50.580
I was on my couch and I
was like, this is crazy.

00:03:50.580 --> 00:03:53.464
So I'm going to go and the
least I can do is just go

00:03:53.464 --> 00:03:54.130
for the weekend.

00:03:54.130 --> 00:03:56.440
I was like, I'm going to
out for Saturday and Sunday.

00:03:56.440 --> 00:03:57.860
And I went, and
the second night I

00:03:57.860 --> 00:04:00.109
was in St. Louis was the
first night I got tear gassed

00:04:00.109 --> 00:04:01.390
and I was like, this is wild.

00:04:01.390 --> 00:04:03.869
I'll do whatever I can to
make sure that nobody else has

00:04:03.869 --> 00:04:04.660
to experience this.

00:04:04.660 --> 00:04:06.610
So I quit and did all
these other things.

00:04:06.610 --> 00:04:08.710
And in hindsight now
I'm like, that was--

00:04:08.710 --> 00:04:10.050
like, what was I doing.

00:04:10.050 --> 00:04:12.400
But I did it and so many
other people did it.

00:04:12.400 --> 00:04:14.230
I'm proud that I was
not the only person.

00:04:14.230 --> 00:04:15.969
There were so many
incredible people

00:04:15.969 --> 00:04:18.510
in St. Louis who did whatever
they could to make a difference

00:04:18.510 --> 00:04:21.907
and continue to do that work.

00:04:21.907 --> 00:04:23.740
WILLIAM FLOYD: As a
father of a 12-year-old,

00:04:23.740 --> 00:04:27.007
I can attest, yes,
deodorant is big deal.

00:04:27.007 --> 00:04:28.090
DERAY MCKESSON: It's real.

00:04:28.090 --> 00:04:28.980
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:28.980 --> 00:04:30.729
And you don't want to
hurt their feelings,

00:04:30.729 --> 00:04:33.850
so you're like,
hey, that smell--

00:04:33.850 --> 00:04:35.112
free gifts for class.

00:04:35.112 --> 00:04:36.070
WILLIAM FLOYD: Exactly.

00:04:36.070 --> 00:04:37.870
I have to stand over
him in the bathroom.

00:04:37.870 --> 00:04:43.420
Like, [INAUDIBLE]---- But you
mentioned a little earlier

00:04:43.420 --> 00:04:47.710
about your personal experience
with communities breaking

00:04:47.710 --> 00:04:51.490
and re-knitting them together.

00:04:51.490 --> 00:04:54.500
How does technology
play a role in that

00:04:54.500 --> 00:04:56.791
from your point of view?

00:04:56.791 --> 00:04:58.040
DERAY MCKESSON: So two things.

00:04:58.040 --> 00:05:01.032
One is the platforms and
the second is the people,

00:05:01.032 --> 00:05:02.740
like you all, who make
these things real.

00:05:02.740 --> 00:05:04.549
When I think about Twitter--

00:05:04.549 --> 00:05:05.965
if not for Twitter,
Missouri would

00:05:05.965 --> 00:05:07.965
have tried to convince
you that we didn't exist.

00:05:07.965 --> 00:05:10.420
Literally, if we had not been
able to tell our own stories

00:05:10.420 --> 00:05:11.770
in real time, they
would have been like,

00:05:11.770 --> 00:05:12.770
those people aren't
really out there.

00:05:12.770 --> 00:05:14.144
And you're like,
are you kidding?

00:05:14.144 --> 00:05:17.590
People forget that in August,
September, and October of 2014,

00:05:17.590 --> 00:05:19.452
it was illegal to stand
still in St. Louis.

00:05:19.452 --> 00:05:21.160
So if you saw us
marching, it wasn't only

00:05:21.160 --> 00:05:22.970
that marching was a
really cool thing to do,

00:05:22.970 --> 00:05:24.100
it was the five-second rule.

00:05:24.100 --> 00:05:25.720
So if you sit still for
more than five seconds,

00:05:25.720 --> 00:05:26.800
you were arrested.

00:05:26.800 --> 00:05:29.470
And we remember that
because that was crazy to us

00:05:29.470 --> 00:05:30.300
and that was real.

00:05:30.300 --> 00:05:31.570
And we just adjusted.

00:05:31.570 --> 00:05:34.030
We sued them and it got
deemed unconstitutional.

00:05:34.030 --> 00:05:35.410
But if not for--

00:05:35.410 --> 00:05:37.540
I remember my tweet about
the five-second rule

00:05:37.540 --> 00:05:41.600
was the first public recorded
instance of the rule.

00:05:41.600 --> 00:05:43.450
So when we sued them,
I had to testify.

00:05:43.450 --> 00:05:45.660
And literally the judge
is like, what is Twitter?

00:05:45.660 --> 00:05:47.505
And I'm like, it's Twitter.

00:05:47.505 --> 00:05:48.870
He's like, what is a tweet?

00:05:48.870 --> 00:05:51.416
And we're literally
recounting my tweet thread

00:05:51.416 --> 00:05:52.540
about the five-second rule.

00:05:52.540 --> 00:05:54.592
And if not for
social media, we just

00:05:54.592 --> 00:05:56.050
wouldn't have been
able to do that.

00:05:56.050 --> 00:05:57.610
Jack the CEO of
Twitter is a friend

00:05:57.610 --> 00:05:59.700
and I remember getting a
call from him being like,

00:05:59.700 --> 00:06:01.480
DeRay, we're going to
buy this company that

00:06:01.480 --> 00:06:03.480
is called Perioscope
because we don't have any--

00:06:03.480 --> 00:06:06.820
I remember that call,
but that was late.

00:06:06.820 --> 00:06:07.780
We'd already been in--

00:06:07.780 --> 00:06:09.220
all we could use was Vine.

00:06:09.220 --> 00:06:11.710
So in the beginning,
we'd literally--

00:06:11.710 --> 00:06:13.420
we'd record a video
on our iPhones.

00:06:13.420 --> 00:06:16.010
Then we'd go run off to the
side, upload it in Vine,

00:06:16.010 --> 00:06:18.940
and scroll through trying to
find the best six seconds,

00:06:18.940 --> 00:06:20.080
and then post it online.

00:06:20.080 --> 00:06:23.410
That was our strategy to do,
because there was no Twitter

00:06:23.410 --> 00:06:24.950
Video, there was
no Facebook Live,

00:06:24.950 --> 00:06:26.680
there was no YouTube streaming.

00:06:26.680 --> 00:06:28.472
Those things didn't
exist back then.

00:06:28.472 --> 00:06:30.430
And there are critics of
us who will say things

00:06:30.430 --> 00:06:31.638
like, you chased the cameras.

00:06:31.638 --> 00:06:33.670
And we're like, we
were the cameras.

00:06:33.670 --> 00:06:34.660
We were it.

00:06:34.660 --> 00:06:36.829
We were the people
telling the truth.

00:06:36.829 --> 00:06:37.870
The second part of this--

00:06:37.870 --> 00:06:41.200
it was like the people
in places like this--

00:06:41.200 --> 00:06:43.540
I'm always mindful that
people made these things.

00:06:43.540 --> 00:06:46.360
These things don't just
emerge out of thin air.

00:06:46.360 --> 00:06:49.051
And what I found over
four years is that when

00:06:49.051 --> 00:06:50.050
we think about leaders--

00:06:50.050 --> 00:06:51.640
we often get leaders,
whether they're

00:06:51.640 --> 00:06:55.210
leaders in the country, not
this guy, but other people,

00:06:55.210 --> 00:06:57.460
or leaders of companies--
and they do things like,

00:06:57.460 --> 00:06:59.050
we're everybody's CEO.

00:06:59.050 --> 00:07:00.971
We don't just lead
the black people

00:07:00.971 --> 00:07:02.470
or the black and
brown people, we're

00:07:02.470 --> 00:07:05.050
everybody-- they use that
language as if that's supposed

00:07:05.050 --> 00:07:06.910
to be some inclusive statement.

00:07:06.910 --> 00:07:09.250
But the reality would be if
you were everybody's CEO,

00:07:09.250 --> 00:07:11.650
you would be marshaling
and marching white people

00:07:11.650 --> 00:07:13.150
to a vision of
equity and justice.

00:07:13.150 --> 00:07:16.550
Because that would be what
leadership looks like.

00:07:16.550 --> 00:07:18.150
I think what you
find in places--

00:07:18.150 --> 00:07:20.470
I've definitely seen tech
companies hide behind

00:07:20.470 --> 00:07:24.220
this vision of inclusivity that
is actually not about equity,

00:07:24.220 --> 00:07:27.580
it's not about justice, but it's
this idea that tech is neutral.

00:07:27.580 --> 00:07:30.100
You're like, none of
this stuff is neutral.

00:07:30.100 --> 00:07:33.700
So I worry about what that
looks like in companies

00:07:33.700 --> 00:07:35.810
across the tech community.

00:07:35.810 --> 00:07:38.020
And the second is, what
is people's proximity

00:07:38.020 --> 00:07:39.079
to these issues?

00:07:39.079 --> 00:07:40.870
So you see a lot of
companies who are like,

00:07:40.870 --> 00:07:42.209
we care and da, da, da.

00:07:42.209 --> 00:07:44.500
There are a lot of people
who think the country got bad

00:07:44.500 --> 00:07:45.610
with the Muslim ban.

00:07:45.610 --> 00:07:47.400
And the country has
been bad way before--

00:07:47.400 --> 00:07:48.920
the Muslim ban is bad.

00:07:48.920 --> 00:07:51.430
That is not the beginning
of the bad, though.

00:07:51.430 --> 00:07:54.602
Or it takes a tragedy
hitting one set of employees

00:07:54.602 --> 00:07:56.560
for people to be like,
oh, my god, the country.

00:07:56.560 --> 00:07:58.960
And you're like, how close
are you to these issues

00:07:58.960 --> 00:08:01.010
that you say you
care about everyday?

00:08:01.010 --> 00:08:02.630
And we actually
can be using tech

00:08:02.630 --> 00:08:05.590
to do something really
interesting and cool about.

00:08:05.590 --> 00:08:07.750
I worry about what
that looks like.

00:08:07.750 --> 00:08:10.190
As somebody who's not in tech,
I know what the issues are.

00:08:10.190 --> 00:08:12.820
I want to believe that if people
who knew how to do something

00:08:12.820 --> 00:08:15.100
in a tech space-- just
knew the issues better,

00:08:15.100 --> 00:08:16.720
they'd be able to
help us brainstorm.

00:08:16.720 --> 00:08:18.940
So you think about, what
does it mean in California

00:08:18.940 --> 00:08:22.270
that 1 in 11 homicides is
committed by an officer

00:08:22.270 --> 00:08:23.860
or a third of all
the people killed

00:08:23.860 --> 00:08:25.210
by a stranger in this
country is actually

00:08:25.210 --> 00:08:26.334
killed by a police officer?

00:08:26.334 --> 00:08:29.377
Those are wild things.

00:08:29.377 --> 00:08:31.210
And want to believe
that we could figure out

00:08:31.210 --> 00:08:33.159
how to capture data better
or we could figure out how

00:08:33.159 --> 00:08:34.480
to visualize this stuff better.

00:08:34.480 --> 00:08:36.580
If you get killed in this
country and a newspaper

00:08:36.580 --> 00:08:37.990
doesn't write about
you, you literally

00:08:37.990 --> 00:08:39.100
are not in the dataset--

00:08:39.100 --> 00:08:40.132
you don't exist.

00:08:40.132 --> 00:08:42.340
So any number you've ever
heard about police violence

00:08:42.340 --> 00:08:44.499
comes from the aggregate
of newspaper reports.

00:08:44.499 --> 00:08:46.540
There are two years in
Florida recently that they

00:08:46.540 --> 00:08:48.700
reported no killings by police.

00:08:48.700 --> 00:08:50.590
You're like, well, we
know that's not true.

00:08:50.590 --> 00:08:51.910
That's just a lie.

00:08:51.910 --> 00:08:54.340
So how do we help people
like you get close enough

00:08:54.340 --> 00:08:58.030
to the issues so you can help us
brainstorm real systemic things

00:08:58.030 --> 00:08:59.290
to do something about it?

00:08:59.290 --> 00:09:01.330
BONITA STEWART: So
it's interesting

00:09:01.330 --> 00:09:04.630
when you think about
a role of technology.

00:09:04.630 --> 00:09:05.720
My husband always jokes--

00:09:05.720 --> 00:09:08.140
he said, who would have
thought Steve Jobs--

00:09:08.140 --> 00:09:14.890
if he only knew that he was the
original purveyor of justice.

00:09:14.890 --> 00:09:18.610
Because with the
invention of the mobile--

00:09:18.610 --> 00:09:20.490
the iPhone was a real start.

00:09:20.490 --> 00:09:22.260
And then aggregating
all of the apps,

00:09:22.260 --> 00:09:25.350
such as Twitter and
Instagram and YouTube--

00:09:25.350 --> 00:09:27.930
all of this in
terms of technology

00:09:27.930 --> 00:09:30.750
and putting it in
the hands of people.

00:09:30.750 --> 00:09:32.840
You talk a little
bit about the truth.

00:09:32.840 --> 00:09:34.920
And there's different
sides of it.

00:09:34.920 --> 00:09:38.410
One, in terms of now
everyone is carrying

00:09:38.410 --> 00:09:42.450
the device, the device
that can either speak

00:09:42.450 --> 00:09:44.550
to truth or in some cases--

00:09:44.550 --> 00:09:46.210
one of the areas that
we're focused on,

00:09:46.210 --> 00:09:48.480
which we announced with
the Google News initiative

00:09:48.480 --> 00:09:52.890
is around media literacy,
so that people understand

00:09:52.890 --> 00:09:57.000
what is the truth, being
a big supporter of quality

00:09:57.000 --> 00:09:57.930
journalism.

00:09:57.930 --> 00:10:01.920
So how are you thinking
about technology

00:10:01.920 --> 00:10:04.960
and driving the truth?

00:10:04.960 --> 00:10:06.870
And what role, quite
frankly, could we

00:10:06.870 --> 00:10:09.510
play as a technology company?

00:10:09.510 --> 00:10:13.440
Because now there's things that
are popping up because people

00:10:13.440 --> 00:10:14.550
have the devices.

00:10:14.550 --> 00:10:17.490
And we could probably
turn on the news tonight

00:10:17.490 --> 00:10:21.840
and there will be some
story about someone

00:10:21.840 --> 00:10:23.880
that has been
recorded, and they're

00:10:23.880 --> 00:10:25.890
trying to explain the truth.

00:10:25.890 --> 00:10:30.540
And I do think particularly with
under-represented minorities,

00:10:30.540 --> 00:10:35.190
quite frankly, that becomes,
for us, a source of truth.

00:10:35.190 --> 00:10:40.150
So how are you thinking about
the literacy, the truth,

00:10:40.150 --> 00:10:42.575
and then the technology
all combined?

00:10:42.575 --> 00:10:43.950
DERAY MCKESSON:
Yeah, so we never

00:10:43.950 --> 00:10:46.200
want to confuse
awareness for action.

00:10:46.200 --> 00:10:48.360
Understanding the problem
is a part of the work

00:10:48.360 --> 00:10:50.100
and seeing that the
world is screwed up

00:10:50.100 --> 00:10:51.600
has to be the first step.

00:10:51.600 --> 00:10:53.308
There are some people
who think that that

00:10:53.308 --> 00:10:54.600
is the whole equation, though.

00:10:54.600 --> 00:10:56.180
We just know that
that is not true.

00:10:56.180 --> 00:10:57.659
Especially four
years later, if you

00:10:57.659 --> 00:10:59.700
see another video of the
police killing somebody,

00:10:59.700 --> 00:11:03.060
if you're shocked now,
it's like, where were you?

00:11:03.060 --> 00:11:05.600
That is not necessarily a
special thing in this moment.

00:11:05.600 --> 00:11:08.130
What we'd also say though
is that there are people who

00:11:08.130 --> 00:11:10.800
have yet to understand that
this is not a system of chances,

00:11:10.800 --> 00:11:12.480
this is not a
system of constance,

00:11:12.480 --> 00:11:14.277
this is a system of choices.

00:11:14.277 --> 00:11:16.110
The best thing that we
can do is help people

00:11:16.110 --> 00:11:18.570
see what those choices were
that have been made before

00:11:18.570 --> 00:11:20.920
to set us up to make a
different set of choices.

00:11:20.920 --> 00:11:22.780
That is what we think
is really important.

00:11:22.780 --> 00:11:24.572
So we think about the
police as an example.

00:11:24.572 --> 00:11:26.154
Four years ago I
would have been like,

00:11:26.154 --> 00:11:27.840
it's a screwed up
system with bad people

00:11:27.840 --> 00:11:29.190
making bad decisions.

00:11:29.190 --> 00:11:31.270
Now I'm like, the
game is just rigged.

00:11:31.270 --> 00:11:33.090
So you look at California--

00:11:33.090 --> 00:11:35.340
California has a law that
says any investigation

00:11:35.340 --> 00:11:37.590
of an officer that lasts
more than a year can never

00:11:37.590 --> 00:11:40.150
result in discipline
regardless of the outcome.

00:11:40.150 --> 00:11:41.510
That just doesn't make--

00:11:41.510 --> 00:11:43.200
that's like a
different set of rules.

00:11:43.200 --> 00:11:44.700
In Cleveland,
disciplinary records

00:11:44.700 --> 00:11:46.650
are destroyed after 60 days.

00:11:46.650 --> 00:11:49.050
After one year,
different set of rules.

00:11:49.050 --> 00:11:51.685
We're just not actually
playing the same game.

00:11:51.685 --> 00:11:54.724
And what we've started to do
is help people figure out,

00:11:54.724 --> 00:11:56.140
here's a game
that's being played.

00:11:56.140 --> 00:11:57.750
I think that's one of the things
that the right does really

00:11:57.750 --> 00:11:58.280
well.

00:11:58.280 --> 00:12:00.030
They're very quiet
about it, but they just

00:12:00.030 --> 00:12:01.990
change the playing field.

00:12:01.990 --> 00:12:04.920
We have been seduce to believe
that the best argument wins--

00:12:04.920 --> 00:12:07.290
if we make the best
case and da, da, da.

00:12:07.290 --> 00:12:08.700
The best argument doesn't win.

00:12:08.700 --> 00:12:10.290
The argument that's
beat into people's

00:12:10.290 --> 00:12:12.420
head over and over,
that is what wins.

00:12:12.420 --> 00:12:15.150
I think that we've forgotten
how to do that sometimes.

00:12:15.150 --> 00:12:16.950
When I think about
the role of tech,

00:12:16.950 --> 00:12:19.107
I think there's some huge
data things that people

00:12:19.107 --> 00:12:19.940
could be working on.

00:12:19.940 --> 00:12:22.590
So you've probably heard people
talk about bail reform and all

00:12:22.590 --> 00:12:23.640
this stuff with bail.

00:12:23.640 --> 00:12:25.530
There's actually
very little data

00:12:25.530 --> 00:12:27.060
about bail-- it
just doesn't exist.

00:12:27.060 --> 00:12:30.570
So we know that when people go
before the judge or the bond

00:12:30.570 --> 00:12:32.890
hearing or whatever, that
there's a stenographer taking

00:12:32.890 --> 00:12:34.030
down everything.

00:12:34.030 --> 00:12:37.530
But that the only place that
the bail amounts are recorded.

00:12:37.530 --> 00:12:41.370
So you've never seen a
study on bail by judge.

00:12:41.370 --> 00:12:42.790
You've never seen
a study on bail

00:12:42.790 --> 00:12:48.000
by any demographic indicator,
because there is no data.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:50.690
So there's a ton of stuff
where there's just not data,

00:12:50.690 --> 00:12:52.650
but we know these
issues are things.

00:12:52.650 --> 00:12:55.934
If I ask you right now, what's
a felony, what would you say?

00:12:55.934 --> 00:12:57.850
WILLIAM FLOYD: What's
the technical definition

00:12:57.850 --> 00:12:57.970
of a felony?

00:12:57.970 --> 00:13:00.160
DERAY MCKESSON: Give me
an example of a felony.

00:13:00.160 --> 00:13:01.330
WILLIAM FLOYD:
Breaking and entering.

00:13:01.330 --> 00:13:02.050
DERAY MCKESSON:
Breaking and entering.

00:13:02.050 --> 00:13:03.300
WILLIAM FLOYD: Stealing a car.

00:13:03.300 --> 00:13:04.900
DERAY MCKESSON: Stealing a car.

00:13:04.900 --> 00:13:06.040
That, to a certain extent.

00:13:06.040 --> 00:13:06.915
What would about you?

00:13:10.700 --> 00:13:13.160
BONITA STEWART: If you
were robbing a bank.

00:13:13.160 --> 00:13:15.059
DERAY MCKESSON: Robbing a bank.

00:13:15.059 --> 00:13:16.850
Well, you ask most
people, what's a felony,

00:13:16.850 --> 00:13:18.170
they say these big things.

00:13:18.170 --> 00:13:20.560
They're like, blowing up a
building, killing 10 people,

00:13:20.560 --> 00:13:21.580
robbing a bank.

00:13:21.580 --> 00:13:24.890
In Virginia, up until this year,
theft over $200 is a felony.

00:13:24.890 --> 00:13:27.332
In Florida, to this day,
theft over $300 is a felony.

00:13:27.332 --> 00:13:29.540
And in both of those states,
when you become a felon,

00:13:29.540 --> 00:13:31.500
you permanently lose
the right to vote.

00:13:31.500 --> 00:13:32.180
That is wild.

00:13:35.240 --> 00:13:37.100
We've been conditioned
to think about felons

00:13:37.100 --> 00:13:39.680
as people who have
killed 10 people, smiled,

00:13:39.680 --> 00:13:42.110
and taken a picture.

00:13:42.110 --> 00:13:44.440
That's what you
think about a felon.

00:13:44.440 --> 00:13:48.770
A felony is stealing
a Chromebook, an iPod.

00:13:48.770 --> 00:13:53.450
That is how people are being
disenfranchised and get scaled.

00:13:53.450 --> 00:13:56.210
But that's actually not the
story that you hear the most.

00:13:56.210 --> 00:14:00.027
In Oklahoma, up until 2001,
theft over $50 was a felony.

00:14:00.027 --> 00:14:01.610
So the way that we've
been conditioned

00:14:01.610 --> 00:14:03.540
to think about these
problems is a real issue.

00:14:03.540 --> 00:14:06.139
So what we would say is that
people in tech, people who know

00:14:06.139 --> 00:14:07.430
how to look at aggregate data--

00:14:07.430 --> 00:14:10.040
the more that we can uncover
and unearth these things

00:14:10.040 --> 00:14:11.660
and visualize them
in a way that helps

00:14:11.660 --> 00:14:14.420
people realize that the only
radical thing is the fact

00:14:14.420 --> 00:14:15.976
that we are talking about it.

00:14:15.976 --> 00:14:17.600
The fact that we're
fighting the system

00:14:17.600 --> 00:14:18.682
is not the radical piece.

00:14:18.682 --> 00:14:20.390
The fact that we have
to fight the system

00:14:20.390 --> 00:14:22.970
is the crazy radical
thing in the first place.

00:14:22.970 --> 00:14:24.620
But there are all
these minor things

00:14:24.620 --> 00:14:25.310
that people just don't know.

00:14:25.310 --> 00:14:27.730
The last thing I'll say is,
how many people are on a jury?

00:14:27.730 --> 00:14:29.075
This is not a trick question.

00:14:29.075 --> 00:14:30.200
WILLIAM FLOYD: I have been.

00:14:30.200 --> 00:14:30.850
DERAY MCKESSON: How many people?

00:14:30.850 --> 00:14:31.391
No, how many?

00:14:31.391 --> 00:14:32.580
WILLIAM FLOYD: Oh, how many?

00:14:32.580 --> 00:14:33.080
12.

00:14:33.080 --> 00:14:33.990
DERAY MCKESSON: He's
like, I was one.

00:14:33.990 --> 00:14:34.489
Yes.

00:14:34.489 --> 00:14:35.151
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:35.151 --> 00:14:37.284
BONITA STEWART: It's
like, "12 Angry Men."

00:14:37.284 --> 00:14:38.575
That's how you can remember it.

00:14:38.575 --> 00:14:39.260
DERAY MCKESSON:
There are two states

00:14:39.260 --> 00:14:41.510
in the country where it only
takes 10 of the 12 people

00:14:41.510 --> 00:14:42.870
to convict you of a felony.

00:14:42.870 --> 00:14:44.870
So in Louisiana, you can
get convicted with life

00:14:44.870 --> 00:14:48.410
without the possibility
of parole in a 10-2 vote,

00:14:48.410 --> 00:14:49.410
which is so wild.

00:14:49.410 --> 00:14:51.510
In Louisiana, it's directly
tied to integration.

00:14:51.510 --> 00:14:53.551
That when black people
started sitting on juries,

00:14:53.551 --> 00:14:55.554
they literally held a
constitutional convention

00:14:55.554 --> 00:14:56.970
so they could
change the threshold

00:14:56.970 --> 00:14:59.636
so that black people would never
be able to lower the conviction

00:14:59.636 --> 00:15:00.257
rate.

00:15:00.257 --> 00:15:01.340
It's Louisiana and Oregon.

00:15:01.340 --> 00:15:02.830
In Oregon, it was about Jews.

00:15:02.830 --> 00:15:04.880
Oregon is the only state
that banned black people

00:15:04.880 --> 00:15:06.290
from living in the state.

00:15:06.290 --> 00:15:08.123
They had already
discriminated against some,

00:15:08.123 --> 00:15:09.820
so juries weren't the
best way to do it.

00:15:09.820 --> 00:15:11.990
But they did it for Jews.

00:15:11.990 --> 00:15:12.610
That is nuts.

00:15:12.610 --> 00:15:15.305
So to this day, in
Louisiana right now--

00:15:15.305 --> 00:15:18.430
and hopefully it'll get changed
in November because it'll be up

00:15:18.430 --> 00:15:19.490
at the ballot--

00:15:19.490 --> 00:15:20.684
it only takes 10 people.

00:15:20.684 --> 00:15:22.100
And I only found
out because I did

00:15:22.100 --> 00:15:26.270
a 6-hour tour of Angola,
which is the biggest prison

00:15:26.270 --> 00:15:29.150
complex in the country.

00:15:29.150 --> 00:15:31.910
And I was I was asking one of
the inmates, what don't I know?

00:15:31.910 --> 00:15:33.470
And he was like, you probably
don't know that it only takes

00:15:33.470 --> 00:15:34.970
10 people to send us here.

00:15:34.970 --> 00:15:36.445
That is nuts.

00:15:36.445 --> 00:15:37.820
There are these
structural things

00:15:37.820 --> 00:15:39.630
that don't make the
public conversation,

00:15:39.630 --> 00:15:42.800
but actually are bringing
more people into the net.

00:15:42.800 --> 00:15:44.240
And we don't talk about those.

00:15:44.240 --> 00:15:47.780
We try to spend more time on
those things now than the stuff

00:15:47.780 --> 00:15:50.510
that you see everyday
in the newspaper.

00:15:50.510 --> 00:15:53.840
WILLIAM FLOYD: Your comment
about awareness and action--

00:15:53.840 --> 00:15:57.740
our forum today is actually
to tie those two together.

00:15:57.740 --> 00:16:00.830
Because you're right,
education and awareness--

00:16:00.830 --> 00:16:02.220
we're beyond that.

00:16:02.220 --> 00:16:04.730
And I speak
personally, and I think

00:16:04.730 --> 00:16:06.530
for many Googlers
in the room, they're

00:16:06.530 --> 00:16:09.410
looking for ways to
connect and to drive

00:16:09.410 --> 00:16:12.440
their awareness
and their outrage

00:16:12.440 --> 00:16:15.740
into something that's
very constructive.

00:16:15.740 --> 00:16:17.720
Case in point, you
wrote the thing

00:16:17.720 --> 00:16:21.980
about technology and data.

00:16:21.980 --> 00:16:23.630
I think one of the
organizations that's

00:16:23.630 --> 00:16:28.220
here today that's tabling
outside after our talks is

00:16:28.220 --> 00:16:29.522
the Vera Institute of Justice.

00:16:29.522 --> 00:16:30.980
DERAY MCKESSON:
Yeah, we love Vera.

00:16:30.980 --> 00:16:31.910
WILLIAM FLOYD: Yeah.

00:16:31.910 --> 00:16:34.580
I sit on the board of the
Vera Institute of Justice.

00:16:34.580 --> 00:16:37.430
And Google is
partnering with Vera

00:16:37.430 --> 00:16:43.560
to do a project to
illuminate and bring out

00:16:43.560 --> 00:16:47.600
how mass incarceration actually
is being driven by smaller

00:16:47.600 --> 00:16:52.130
regional, smaller jurisdictions
around the country, not

00:16:52.130 --> 00:16:52.880
the big cities.

00:16:52.880 --> 00:16:55.760
Actually, the big cities
are doing the lot,

00:16:55.760 --> 00:16:57.980
either because they got
woke or they realize they

00:16:57.980 --> 00:16:59.490
don't have the money to do it--

00:16:59.490 --> 00:17:02.060
to deemphasize incarceration.

00:17:02.060 --> 00:17:04.280
It's actually the
smaller jurisdictions

00:17:04.280 --> 00:17:08.240
around the country, mostly in
red states and rural areas,

00:17:08.240 --> 00:17:11.690
that, in the aggregate, is
driving up mass incarceration.

00:17:11.690 --> 00:17:14.530
And our thought is let's
get the data out there.

00:17:14.530 --> 00:17:18.619
Let's go out and educate
politicians and those folks who

00:17:18.619 --> 00:17:21.260
live in those communities
on how they're actually

00:17:21.260 --> 00:17:26.180
contributing to this overall
emphasis on incarceration.

00:17:28.820 --> 00:17:30.530
Just wanted to make that plug.

00:17:30.530 --> 00:17:36.620
But I did want to ask you a
question though about stories

00:17:36.620 --> 00:17:41.990
and surfacing stories, which
you do in your podcast.

00:17:41.990 --> 00:17:47.450
To Bonita's point
about media literacy--

00:17:47.450 --> 00:17:50.780
there's a role there of
surfacing news stories that

00:17:50.780 --> 00:17:56.330
are actually getting suppressed
because of the deluge of what

00:17:56.330 --> 00:17:58.700
we're reading in the
newspapers that are important.

00:17:58.700 --> 00:18:00.680
Can you tell us a
little bit about that,

00:18:00.680 --> 00:18:03.477
like some stories that
you've recently come across?

00:18:03.477 --> 00:18:04.310
DERAY MCKESSON: Yes.

00:18:04.310 --> 00:18:05.550
The podcast is called
"Pod Save The People."

00:18:05.550 --> 00:18:06.258
Shout out to Sam.

00:18:06.258 --> 00:18:07.550
Sam is on the podcast, too.

00:18:07.550 --> 00:18:10.812
Sam is here-- love Sam.

00:18:10.812 --> 00:18:12.520
So when I started the
podcast a year ago,

00:18:12.520 --> 00:18:14.830
I wanted the first half to be
about all the news you don't

00:18:14.830 --> 00:18:16.120
know that's really important.

00:18:16.120 --> 00:18:18.080
You're going to hear about Trump
whether you want to or not.

00:18:18.080 --> 00:18:19.600
So we didn't feel like we needed
to spend a whole lot of time

00:18:19.600 --> 00:18:21.940
on him, because you're
going to hear him anyway.

00:18:25.211 --> 00:18:26.710
The way it works
is the four of us--

00:18:26.710 --> 00:18:28.330
everybody picks their
piece of news every week,

00:18:28.330 --> 00:18:29.240
they put it in the group chat.

00:18:29.240 --> 00:18:31.850
We don't hear your argument
about the news until we record.

00:18:31.850 --> 00:18:34.522
So we're learning
when you say it.

00:18:34.522 --> 00:18:35.980
And there's some
things-- there was

00:18:35.980 --> 00:18:38.440
a study that says that there's
pushing back on the idea

00:18:38.440 --> 00:18:41.292
that people get more
conservative as they get older.

00:18:41.292 --> 00:18:43.750
And what the study is saying
is that poor people and people

00:18:43.750 --> 00:18:46.190
of color actually
just never get older.

00:18:46.190 --> 00:18:48.604
So it's not that people are
getting more conservative,

00:18:48.604 --> 00:18:51.270
it's that some people just never
have the luxury of getting old.

00:18:51.270 --> 00:18:53.140
And you're like, hadn't
thought about that--

00:18:53.140 --> 00:18:54.340
that's really interesting.

00:18:54.340 --> 00:18:57.040
Or on the news tomorrow--
you probably heard

00:18:57.040 --> 00:18:59.570
about the straw ban in Seattle.

00:18:59.570 --> 00:19:01.570
People talk about it as
a really important thing

00:19:01.570 --> 00:19:02.450
for the environment.

00:19:02.450 --> 00:19:04.325
The disability community
is really frustrated

00:19:04.325 --> 00:19:08.070
because there are people with
disabilities who needs straws.

00:19:08.070 --> 00:19:10.840
And when you have now
made straws illegal,

00:19:10.840 --> 00:19:13.420
what happens for people
who can't use their hands,

00:19:13.420 --> 00:19:15.375
for people who need
disposable straws?

00:19:15.375 --> 00:19:17.500
A permanent straw is not
actually the most hygienic

00:19:17.500 --> 00:19:18.560
for a set of people.

00:19:18.560 --> 00:19:21.061
So trying to look at these
issues that people take for

00:19:21.061 --> 00:19:23.060
granted and look at them
from a different angle.

00:19:23.060 --> 00:19:24.851
The straw story is
really interesting, too,

00:19:24.851 --> 00:19:27.490
because it's all predicated on
this study that says that we

00:19:27.490 --> 00:19:29.590
use 500 million straws a day.

00:19:29.590 --> 00:19:31.390
When you ask about
the study, the study

00:19:31.390 --> 00:19:34.820
comes from a nine-year-old
who did a phone survey.

00:19:34.820 --> 00:19:35.940
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:35.940 --> 00:19:38.680
That literally is the
source of the study.

00:19:38.680 --> 00:19:41.529
So Snopes and everybody
has tried to figure out,

00:19:41.529 --> 00:19:42.820
what's the source of the study?

00:19:42.820 --> 00:19:44.694
And the guy's like, I
did it when I was nine.

00:19:44.694 --> 00:19:48.280
He's 16 now and
people are like--

00:19:48.280 --> 00:19:51.470
every major news organization
has cited this study

00:19:51.470 --> 00:19:53.050
as 500 million straws a day.

00:19:53.050 --> 00:19:56.060
And you're like, uh--

00:19:56.060 --> 00:19:59.130
was that a science fair project?

00:19:59.130 --> 00:20:00.770
Where did the straw
study come from?

00:20:00.770 --> 00:20:04.270
So we try and look at these
issues from a different angle,

00:20:04.270 --> 00:20:06.989
hopefully setting listeners up
with a different set of skills

00:20:06.989 --> 00:20:08.530
to be able to ask
questions and think

00:20:08.530 --> 00:20:11.504
about things in a way they
might not have otherwise.

