00:20:22.990 --> 00:20:25.610
because it was an hour and
the whole podcast is an hour.

00:20:25.610 --> 00:20:27.985
But I asked her this
question about her mom.

00:20:27.985 --> 00:20:29.860
I'm like, was your mom
there on election day?

00:20:29.860 --> 00:20:31.485
And she's like, yeah,
my mom was there.

00:20:31.485 --> 00:20:33.693
And there wasn't really a
story about election night.

00:20:33.693 --> 00:20:35.500
She was like, my mom
stayed the next day,

00:20:35.500 --> 00:20:37.450
and she's like, I was
doing all this media--

00:20:37.450 --> 00:20:38.530
this is more media
than I've ever

00:20:38.530 --> 00:20:39.780
done so I wasn't at the house.

00:20:39.780 --> 00:20:42.240
And she's like, my mom
calls and is like, hey,

00:20:42.240 --> 00:20:43.780
the "New York
Post" just came by.

00:20:43.780 --> 00:20:44.920
She's like, OK, how was it?

00:20:44.920 --> 00:20:48.390
She was like, oh, chill
interview-- not a big deal.

00:20:48.390 --> 00:20:49.274
And she's like, OK.

00:20:49.274 --> 00:20:50.690
Next day, front
page of the "Post"

00:20:50.690 --> 00:20:52.690
is, Ocasio-Cortez
running for president.

00:20:52.690 --> 00:20:56.220
And she was like, mom,
what did you say to them?

00:20:56.220 --> 00:20:58.905
And she's like, I told them my
baby could be present one day.

00:20:58.905 --> 00:20:59.950
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:59.950 --> 00:21:02.110
She's like, never,
ever talk to the press.

00:21:02.110 --> 00:21:03.220
You're banned.

00:21:03.220 --> 00:21:06.710
If people-- just tell
them I'm not home.

00:21:06.710 --> 00:21:10.140
She had other things
to say about politics.

00:21:10.140 --> 00:21:13.349
But I thought she
was so great with it.

00:21:13.349 --> 00:21:15.640
But it was this conversation
when I started the podcast

00:21:15.640 --> 00:21:18.190
about, how do we invite
people into conversations

00:21:18.190 --> 00:21:20.590
that they might not
be a part of before?

00:21:20.590 --> 00:21:24.055
So Ocasio-Cortez, we had
Snowden on really early.

00:21:24.055 --> 00:21:26.680
He was the third interview I did
to talk about the intersection

00:21:26.680 --> 00:21:28.220
of security and race.

00:21:28.220 --> 00:21:30.179
Because Snowden doesn't
really talk about race.

00:21:30.179 --> 00:21:31.678
But I wanted to
create a space so we

00:21:31.678 --> 00:21:33.940
can talk about what race
looks like in the security

00:21:33.940 --> 00:21:35.041
conversation.

00:21:35.041 --> 00:21:36.540
And those sort of
things-- we wanted

00:21:36.540 --> 00:21:40.600
to be a home and a place led by
activists, where we could just

00:21:40.600 --> 00:21:43.487
say what we want that
we believe is true.

00:21:43.487 --> 00:21:45.070
BONITA STEWART: If
you have questions,

00:21:45.070 --> 00:21:48.100
this is an opportunity
to start lining up

00:21:48.100 --> 00:21:50.740
and then we have a few
more questions for DeRay.

00:21:50.740 --> 00:21:53.960
I want to just circle back
on the law enforcement.

00:21:53.960 --> 00:21:56.290
We talked about
podcasts and audio

00:21:56.290 --> 00:21:59.050
and the importance of audio.

00:21:59.050 --> 00:22:04.670
But now, technology is
coming to police enforcement.

00:22:04.670 --> 00:22:10.730
How do you think from an audio
perspective and technology--

00:22:10.730 --> 00:22:16.940
the fact that this is now
being captured with video,

00:22:16.940 --> 00:22:19.430
there's audio.

00:22:19.430 --> 00:22:25.680
What is your view of the
technology in the law

00:22:25.680 --> 00:22:29.970
enforcement and how you think
it will be used or not used?

00:22:29.970 --> 00:22:32.520
Or the consequences we were
talking earlier about--

00:22:32.520 --> 00:22:38.869
are there consequences based
on now having actual proof?

00:22:38.869 --> 00:22:40.410
DERAY MCKESSON: So
I think technology

00:22:40.410 --> 00:22:43.180
has been in policing for better
or for worse for a long time.

00:22:43.180 --> 00:22:44.760
I think body cameras
are the newest

00:22:44.760 --> 00:22:48.180
iteration that most people
have public language about.

00:22:48.180 --> 00:22:51.180
When the Obama administration
was still in play,

00:22:51.180 --> 00:22:52.650
we had been talking
to their team.

00:22:52.650 --> 00:22:54.030
They were partnering
with the university

00:22:54.030 --> 00:22:56.280
to figure out if they could
use the audio specifically

00:22:56.280 --> 00:22:58.680
to measure aggression
in an officer's voice.

00:22:58.680 --> 00:23:00.570
So not just looking
at the video,

00:23:00.570 --> 00:23:03.300
but could we see spikes in
temper and things like that

00:23:03.300 --> 00:23:04.410
just by the audio?

00:23:04.410 --> 00:23:06.150
Which is an interesting
way to think

00:23:06.150 --> 00:23:09.180
about using body cameras that
don't just rely on the footage.

00:23:09.180 --> 00:23:10.570
So that's an interesting thing.

00:23:10.570 --> 00:23:12.774
I think we should follow-up
and see where they are.

00:23:12.774 --> 00:23:14.190
There is new
technology, too, that

00:23:14.190 --> 00:23:19.020
allows to trigger
the body cameras,

00:23:19.020 --> 00:23:20.640
like, when a police
door opens, things

00:23:20.640 --> 00:23:22.110
like that, that don't
require the officer

00:23:22.110 --> 00:23:23.640
to press a button
anymore, but just

00:23:23.640 --> 00:23:26.520
automatically turn on the
dash cam or things like that.

00:23:26.520 --> 00:23:29.490
We're in the minority
in the movement

00:23:29.490 --> 00:23:31.110
conversation about cameras.

00:23:31.110 --> 00:23:34.050
Because a lot of people rightly
are nervous about body cameras

00:23:34.050 --> 00:23:35.780
as being another
tool of surveillance.

00:23:35.780 --> 00:23:39.346
That if community policing
really is your code for putting

00:23:39.346 --> 00:23:41.970
police in black neighborhoods--
because they're not going to be

00:23:41.970 --> 00:23:44.386
on the Upper West Side in the
same way you're putting them

00:23:44.386 --> 00:23:45.490
in other places--

00:23:45.490 --> 00:23:47.790
and if community policing
becomes this idea

00:23:47.790 --> 00:23:50.550
that the police need to know
my kid's name not to kill them.

00:23:50.550 --> 00:23:53.370
You don't need to play football
with my child not to kill him.

00:23:53.370 --> 00:23:56.640
But that is how people use this
idea of community policing.

00:23:56.640 --> 00:23:58.837
If that is the case, you
put cameras on people

00:23:58.837 --> 00:24:01.170
and now you just are surveilling
the whole neighborhood.

00:24:01.170 --> 00:24:02.940
So that is not a good thing.

00:24:02.940 --> 00:24:04.680
What is interesting
about the video thing

00:24:04.680 --> 00:24:07.860
is that in the 1%
of police officers

00:24:07.860 --> 00:24:10.650
who are ever charged
with anything,

00:24:10.650 --> 00:24:12.730
videos are actually
really important.

00:24:12.730 --> 00:24:14.190
So that's where you get stuck.

00:24:14.190 --> 00:24:15.648
It is the likelihood
of you getting

00:24:15.648 --> 00:24:17.310
charged without a video--

00:24:17.310 --> 00:24:19.260
it's probably not happening.

00:24:19.260 --> 00:24:22.020
The video is our
only slight pathway

00:24:22.020 --> 00:24:23.910
to there being some
sort of accountability,

00:24:23.910 --> 00:24:26.880
which is why we veer to
video rather than not video.

00:24:26.880 --> 00:24:29.610
Which is a complicated
piece about it.

00:24:29.610 --> 00:24:32.160
With all the technology
used in policing,

00:24:32.160 --> 00:24:34.470
we believe that there
should be public oversight.

00:24:34.470 --> 00:24:36.690
So what you find
in a lot of cities

00:24:36.690 --> 00:24:39.210
is that the body camera
footage is actually

00:24:39.210 --> 00:24:41.206
under the purview of
the police department.

00:24:41.206 --> 00:24:42.330
Only the police department.

00:24:42.330 --> 00:24:43.620
Nobody has access to it.

00:24:43.620 --> 00:24:46.260
We don't believe that
that is a just way

00:24:46.260 --> 00:24:48.580
to think about
any of this stuff.

00:24:48.580 --> 00:24:49.600
And that is really hard.

00:24:49.600 --> 00:24:50.790
So I that we're
in this new space

00:24:50.790 --> 00:24:52.206
where people now
have the language

00:24:52.206 --> 00:24:54.570
to talk about the technology.

00:24:54.570 --> 00:24:56.910
But the police would advocate
for all types of stuff.

00:24:56.910 --> 00:24:58.320
They want facial recognition.

00:24:58.320 --> 00:25:01.330
It's like, y'all aren't
solving any crimes any better.

00:25:01.330 --> 00:25:03.930
None of that's going to build
the trust that you broke.

00:25:03.930 --> 00:25:05.359
And you broke the trust.

00:25:05.359 --> 00:25:06.900
I'm not convinced
technology is going

00:25:06.900 --> 00:25:09.510
to be the salve
for how you rebuild

00:25:09.510 --> 00:25:11.790
that trust in communities,
even if police want

00:25:11.790 --> 00:25:13.718
that to be the magic bullet.

00:25:13.718 --> 00:25:16.650
BONITA STEWART: Interesting.

00:25:16.650 --> 00:25:19.490
WILLIAM FLOYD: Why
don't we go to some Q&amp;A

00:25:19.490 --> 00:25:20.770
before we come to a close.

00:25:20.770 --> 00:25:21.853
BONITA STEWART: Johnathan.

00:25:21.853 --> 00:25:23.895
WILLIAM FLOYD: Johnathan,
why don't you start us.

00:25:23.895 --> 00:25:26.394
AUDIENCE: First of all, I just
want to say thank you, DeRay,

00:25:26.394 --> 00:25:28.770
not only for being here today
and sharing all your wisdom

00:25:28.770 --> 00:25:31.940
with us, but for the sacrifices
that you've put yourself

00:25:31.940 --> 00:25:33.690
in front of and the
sacrifices that you've

00:25:33.690 --> 00:25:34.606
made in this movement.

00:25:34.606 --> 00:25:36.660
Because you've put
your body, your health,

00:25:36.660 --> 00:25:38.786
and your time on the
line time and time again.

00:25:38.786 --> 00:25:40.410
So personally, I just
want to thank you

00:25:40.410 --> 00:25:41.868
for that, because
that is something

00:25:41.868 --> 00:25:45.270
that often goes overlooked
when we talk about this work.

00:25:45.270 --> 00:25:47.140
Two quick questions for you.

00:25:47.140 --> 00:25:51.270
First question being, when we
think about the work of making

00:25:51.270 --> 00:25:53.880
change scalable-- something at
Google, we always talk about,

00:25:53.880 --> 00:25:56.320
how can we solve
problems at scale?

00:25:56.320 --> 00:25:58.927
And so oftentimes, people
grab on to one thing.

00:25:58.927 --> 00:26:01.260
Well, if we get body cameras,
that will solve the issue.

00:26:01.260 --> 00:26:04.080
Or if we make sure that we
have community policing,

00:26:04.080 --> 00:26:05.260
that will solve the issue.

00:26:05.260 --> 00:26:09.130
But these issues are much
deeper than just one solution.

00:26:09.130 --> 00:26:10.872
So how, when you have
these conversations

00:26:10.872 --> 00:26:12.330
and try to get
people involved, how

00:26:12.330 --> 00:26:15.540
do you keep a level of
depth to the conversation,

00:26:15.540 --> 00:26:17.370
but still make it
attainable for people

00:26:17.370 --> 00:26:19.110
to feel like, I feel
I can get involved--

00:26:19.110 --> 00:26:21.690
this isn't too big enough
for me to get involved.

00:26:21.690 --> 00:26:23.700
And the second
question I have is,

00:26:23.700 --> 00:26:25.530
you have a popular
saying on the podcast

00:26:25.530 --> 00:26:27.720
that we each owe a debt
that we can never pay back.

00:26:27.720 --> 00:26:29.610
So it's our job
to pay it forward

00:26:29.610 --> 00:26:31.650
and to pay it to
the next generation.

00:26:31.650 --> 00:26:34.080
How do you live that and
how do you pay it forward?

00:26:34.080 --> 00:26:35.580
DERAY MCKESSON: So
one of the things

00:26:35.580 --> 00:26:36.525
I didn't say about
the technology thing

00:26:36.525 --> 00:26:39.300
that I just thought of is
that what we learned recently

00:26:39.300 --> 00:26:42.630
is that the biggest producer
of body cameras in the country

00:26:42.630 --> 00:26:47.370
actually intentionally makes
the quality of the body cameras

00:26:47.370 --> 00:26:50.730
really awful, to not be
better than the human eye.

00:26:50.730 --> 00:26:53.086
Because they want it
to be so that officers

00:26:53.086 --> 00:26:54.960
can say that they were
confused about the toy

00:26:54.960 --> 00:26:56.532
gun or the real gun.

00:26:56.532 --> 00:26:57.990
But we actually
know the technology

00:26:57.990 --> 00:27:00.180
exists today that can make
the body camera footage

00:27:00.180 --> 00:27:01.450
crystal clear.

00:27:01.450 --> 00:27:04.650
But you've never seen a
crystal clear body camera.

00:27:04.650 --> 00:27:06.689
Not because cameras
are bad in 2018,

00:27:06.689 --> 00:27:08.730
but because they're
intentionally made to be bad.

00:27:08.730 --> 00:27:11.640
So what would it look like if
we believe that body cameras are

00:27:11.640 --> 00:27:14.120
part of the solution for
another company to make them

00:27:14.120 --> 00:27:16.830
with clear footage.

00:27:16.830 --> 00:27:19.080
So that you can't confuse
a toy gun with a real gun.

00:27:19.080 --> 00:27:21.650
Because on the footage we
would see that it is not.

00:27:21.650 --> 00:27:23.580
We learned recently
that they actually

00:27:23.580 --> 00:27:26.970
want the quality to be grainy,
so that there can be confusion.

00:27:26.970 --> 00:27:29.830
Which is a wild, wild thing.

00:27:29.830 --> 00:27:31.860
Your first question
about what do we.

00:27:31.860 --> 00:27:37.380
We believe that 10 years ago, we
didn't know how we got here per

00:27:37.380 --> 00:27:38.750
se, but we knew we were here.

00:27:38.750 --> 00:27:40.650
We knew there was all these
black people getting locked up.

00:27:40.650 --> 00:27:42.525
We knew there was all
these wild disparities.

00:27:42.525 --> 00:27:43.484
But we didn't know how.

00:27:43.484 --> 00:27:45.649
Now we're at a place-- and
this is one of the things

00:27:45.649 --> 00:27:48.150
that Sam and I and Brittany
are trying to figure out.

00:27:48.150 --> 00:27:50.860
What would it be like to map
all the things that got us here?

00:27:50.860 --> 00:27:53.960
So from mapping all
the felony theft

00:27:53.960 --> 00:27:56.640
amounts across the
country to how much

00:27:56.640 --> 00:28:00.440
prison phone calls cost to
all the contracts for ICE.

00:28:00.440 --> 00:28:02.910
What if we create a space
that is like, here's

00:28:02.910 --> 00:28:05.870
how mass incarceration is
upheld in your city and town

00:28:05.870 --> 00:28:08.204
and it's just there for people?

00:28:08.204 --> 00:28:09.870
So activists and
organizers and citizens

00:28:09.870 --> 00:28:13.960
no longer have to spend 10 years
trying to find that random law

00:28:13.960 --> 00:28:15.337
or uncover that thing.

00:28:15.337 --> 00:28:16.920
They actually know
what it is already.

00:28:16.920 --> 00:28:18.420
So they spend their
energy fighting

00:28:18.420 --> 00:28:20.675
it as opposed to finding it.

00:28:20.675 --> 00:28:22.050
And so much of
the work right now

00:28:22.050 --> 00:28:23.880
is people-- you spend all
day trying to find it.

00:28:23.880 --> 00:28:25.546
You're like, I think
this thing is bad--

00:28:25.546 --> 00:28:26.939
I don't know how it got here--

00:28:26.939 --> 00:28:27.480
I don't know.

00:28:27.480 --> 00:28:29.521
But we actually believe
that in this day and age,

00:28:29.521 --> 00:28:30.850
we can actually do that work.

00:28:30.850 --> 00:28:33.210
A set of us can figure out
how to build that thing.

00:28:33.210 --> 00:28:36.060
So you can know the felony
theft amount in your town.

00:28:36.060 --> 00:28:38.791
You can know how many people
were killed by the police.

00:28:38.791 --> 00:28:41.290
I don't know if you remember
when Alton Sterling got killed,

00:28:41.290 --> 00:28:43.690
there was a press conference
by the police chief.

00:28:43.690 --> 00:28:45.270
And the police chief,
one of the things he says

00:28:45.270 --> 00:28:47.490
is like, you should pick up
the phone and file a complaint.

00:28:47.490 --> 00:28:48.755
In Baton Rouge, you
actually can't file

00:28:48.755 --> 00:28:49.880
a complaint over the phone.

00:28:49.880 --> 00:28:52.744
So that was a weird
thing that he said.

00:28:52.744 --> 00:28:54.660
There are a lot of places
in the country where

00:28:54.660 --> 00:28:57.150
you can't file anonymous
complaints against the police.

00:28:57.150 --> 00:28:59.100
Every complaint has
to be signed and you

00:28:59.100 --> 00:29:02.070
have to swear an
oath that it is true.

00:29:02.070 --> 00:29:05.410
Mind you, I can call in 10
anonymous complaints about any

00:29:05.410 --> 00:29:08.040
of you all right now to the
New York City Police Department

00:29:08.040 --> 00:29:09.870
and they would take it as fact.

00:29:09.870 --> 00:29:12.030
So how do we set it
up so that you already

00:29:12.030 --> 00:29:14.520
know what the good and bad is
and you can fight about that?

00:29:14.520 --> 00:29:15.978
And we spent a lot
of time on that.

00:29:15.978 --> 00:29:18.300
We believe that that is a
good on ramp for people.

00:29:18.300 --> 00:29:21.019
So you don't have to spend
all day trying to figure out

00:29:21.019 --> 00:29:22.560
what is bad and what
is not, somebody

00:29:22.560 --> 00:29:23.869
can tell you those things.

00:29:23.869 --> 00:29:25.660
The second thing is
that the more you know,

00:29:25.660 --> 00:29:26.534
the better you'll do.

00:29:26.534 --> 00:29:29.355
And there are people who
believe in immigration stuff

00:29:29.355 --> 00:29:31.105
and don't know anything
about immigration.

00:29:31.105 --> 00:29:33.180
You're like, that's
not really helpful.

00:29:33.180 --> 00:29:35.610
So the closer, the more
proximate you are to an issue--

00:29:35.610 --> 00:29:38.487
you find people, especially
people with skills in this way.

00:29:38.487 --> 00:29:40.320
They start to ask more
questions and they're

00:29:40.320 --> 00:29:42.695
like, let me build a thing or
let me test this thing out,

00:29:42.695 --> 00:29:43.860
or let me partner.

00:29:43.860 --> 00:29:46.920
Those things are actually
really, really powerful.

00:29:46.920 --> 00:29:49.200
The idea of paying it forward--

00:29:49.200 --> 00:29:52.060
what I try to do is, how do we
create space for other people?

00:29:52.060 --> 00:29:54.670
So one of the things about the
pod is that, because it's mine,

00:29:54.670 --> 00:29:56.759
I can get anybody on I want to.

00:29:56.759 --> 00:29:58.800
I was telling them backstage,
I had Stacey Abrams

00:29:58.800 --> 00:30:03.780
on four months before it
was even a thing in Georgia.

00:30:03.780 --> 00:30:05.790
But she was like, I
need to be on early.

00:30:05.790 --> 00:30:07.124
I'm like, got you.

00:30:07.124 --> 00:30:09.540
There's a black guy running
for the governor of Wisconsin.

00:30:09.540 --> 00:30:10.770
I didn't even know he--

00:30:10.770 --> 00:30:13.103
I didn't know there were a
lot of black people in Wisc--

00:30:13.103 --> 00:30:13.890
I didn't know.

00:30:13.890 --> 00:30:15.350
We had him on, he was great.

00:30:15.350 --> 00:30:16.517
He used to be a firefighter.

00:30:16.517 --> 00:30:18.016
We had this whole
great conversation

00:30:18.016 --> 00:30:18.870
about firefighting.

00:30:18.870 --> 00:30:21.200
I asked him, is being a
firefighter on TV anything

00:30:21.200 --> 00:30:22.680
like it is in real life?

00:30:22.680 --> 00:30:24.680
And he's like, no, obviously.

00:30:24.680 --> 00:30:27.260
And he was like, if you
see firefighters on TV

00:30:27.260 --> 00:30:29.930
shows talk in a burning
building, that's

00:30:29.930 --> 00:30:31.025
the craziest thing ever.

00:30:31.025 --> 00:30:31.650
You can't talk.

00:30:31.650 --> 00:30:33.770
