00:41:09.510 --> 00:41:11.093
We both had this
moment like, Sam, you

00:41:11.093 --> 00:41:12.100
should go do her policy.

00:41:12.100 --> 00:41:13.890
Sam, you can't go
because we need you,

00:41:13.890 --> 00:41:15.770
but Ocasio-Cortez
needs you, too.

00:41:15.770 --> 00:41:18.050
So Stacey Abrams, I'm
really hopeful about.

00:41:18.050 --> 00:41:19.550
Mahlon Mitchell,
who's running to be

00:41:19.550 --> 00:41:20.990
the governor of Wisconsin.

00:41:20.990 --> 00:41:23.570
Ben Jealous, who is running to
be the governor of Maryland.

00:41:23.570 --> 00:41:25.230
I'm excited about those people.

00:41:25.230 --> 00:41:25.730
It's hard.

00:41:25.730 --> 00:41:28.919
There's so many candidates
who want to be on the pod.

00:41:28.919 --> 00:41:30.460
I would just have
a pod of candidates

00:41:30.460 --> 00:41:32.870
because there's so many
incredible people running,

00:41:32.870 --> 00:41:35.150
so I just don't
get to all of them.

00:41:35.150 --> 00:41:37.310
But I'm hopeful about
what we could do.

00:41:37.310 --> 00:41:39.910
I'm interested in after
'18 how we actually

00:41:39.910 --> 00:41:41.474
build a basin for 2020.

00:41:41.474 --> 00:41:43.640
How do we do that in a way
that's really thoughtful?

00:41:43.640 --> 00:41:45.440
I think that getting out the
vote and all this stuff for '18

00:41:45.440 --> 00:41:46.070
is really important.

00:41:46.070 --> 00:41:48.110
I'm hopeful that we'll
be successful in taking

00:41:48.110 --> 00:41:49.610
one part of Congress back.

00:41:49.610 --> 00:41:51.950
But the game in 2020--
he could win again.

00:41:51.950 --> 00:41:53.430
And I remember--
I supported him--

00:41:53.430 --> 00:41:54.512
I supp-- I supported him.

00:41:54.512 --> 00:41:55.220
That is not true.

00:41:55.220 --> 00:41:56.300
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:56.300 --> 00:42:00.110
My phone got hacked and I did
tweet out support for Trump.

00:42:00.110 --> 00:42:02.692
But that was because
somebody hacked my phone.

00:42:02.692 --> 00:42:05.150
But I supported Hillary in "The
Washington Post" and people

00:42:05.150 --> 00:42:07.132
really slammed me for--

00:42:07.132 --> 00:42:08.090
why are you doing this?

00:42:08.090 --> 00:42:09.140
She's such a hypocrite.

00:42:09.140 --> 00:42:10.556
It was like, because
he could win.

00:42:10.556 --> 00:42:11.630
This is real.

00:42:11.630 --> 00:42:12.832
I believe him.

00:42:12.832 --> 00:42:15.290
And I remember talking to a
senior member of Hillary's team

00:42:15.290 --> 00:42:17.040
not too long ago, and
she was like, DeRay,

00:42:17.040 --> 00:42:18.960
there are people in the Muslim
community calling us now

00:42:18.960 --> 00:42:21.350
and there are people in all
these racial minorities calling

00:42:21.350 --> 00:42:22.600
us being like, what can we do?

00:42:22.600 --> 00:42:24.800
And she's like, I
tried to tell you all.

00:42:24.800 --> 00:42:27.126
I believe that--
again, about 2020--

00:42:27.126 --> 00:42:29.750
I remember people saying, DeRay,
he doesn't have a ground game.

00:42:29.750 --> 00:42:30.916
He's not doing doorknocking.

00:42:30.916 --> 00:42:33.139
The Trump campaign did none
of the traditional stuff.

00:42:33.139 --> 00:42:35.180
Partly because the Russians
helped them, but also

00:42:35.180 --> 00:42:39.520
because they knew that racism
was enough of a ground game.

00:42:39.520 --> 00:42:41.200
That was actually an
effective strategy.

00:42:41.200 --> 00:42:43.390
And they will be able
to mobilize that again

00:42:43.390 --> 00:42:45.250
in 2020, unless
we figure out how

00:42:45.250 --> 00:42:47.350
to build a different
electorate and tell

00:42:47.350 --> 00:42:49.557
a different story about the
power of people's votes.

00:42:49.557 --> 00:42:51.140
And I think that we
are close to that.

00:42:51.140 --> 00:42:52.676
I don't think that
we're there yet.

00:42:52.676 --> 00:42:54.550
And I was on the transition
team for the DNC,

00:42:54.550 --> 00:42:58.192
so I believe in being on
the inside, da, da, da.

00:42:58.192 --> 00:42:59.900
I don't think they
got the answer either.

00:42:59.900 --> 00:43:01.358
So I'm more committed
to, how do we

00:43:01.358 --> 00:43:04.730
build an infrastructure
outside of the system for 2020?

00:43:04.730 --> 00:43:06.040
And I think that's important.

00:43:06.040 --> 00:43:06.540
And

00:43:06.540 --> 00:43:09.123
Advise that I've gotten that's
stuck with me is this idea of--

00:43:12.961 --> 00:43:14.820
Cleo Wade, who is a
friend and a poet,

00:43:14.820 --> 00:43:18.330
she has this saying that not
every ground is a battleground.

00:43:18.330 --> 00:43:19.350
And I really like that.

00:43:19.350 --> 00:43:21.950
There's some times when
all we've done is fight--

00:43:21.950 --> 00:43:23.489
that's all we know how to do.

00:43:23.489 --> 00:43:25.280
And the fight has to
be a part of the work.

00:43:25.280 --> 00:43:28.760
But there are some people who
every relationship is a battle,

00:43:28.760 --> 00:43:31.340
because they have had to
fight the world for so long.

00:43:31.340 --> 00:43:34.430
And I try and remind myself
that blackness is not only--

00:43:34.430 --> 00:43:36.560
that we are more than
our pain, that we can

00:43:36.560 --> 00:43:37.880
be something beautiful, too.

00:43:37.880 --> 00:43:39.830
And I never glorify--

00:43:39.830 --> 00:43:43.160
people talk about this wave of
activism and like all of it.

00:43:43.160 --> 00:43:45.240
I'm like, yeah, it's a
lot of activism and stuff,

00:43:45.240 --> 00:43:47.960
but I never want to glorify
the trauma that made us be

00:43:47.960 --> 00:43:49.560
so active in the first place.

00:43:49.560 --> 00:43:50.980
So I'm active because I
feel like I've got to be.

00:43:50.980 --> 00:43:52.896
And I'm fighting for
the kids at [INAUDIBLE],,

00:43:52.896 --> 00:43:54.320
I'm fighting for
all these people.

00:43:54.320 --> 00:43:56.320
But I should be able to
go back and be a teacher

00:43:56.320 --> 00:43:59.330
and not have to worry about
the world falling apart.

00:43:59.330 --> 00:44:01.430
I don't glorify the
pain that got us here

00:44:01.430 --> 00:44:03.770
and this idea of
not every ground

00:44:03.770 --> 00:44:05.516
is a battleground stays with me.

00:44:05.516 --> 00:44:07.700
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:44:07.700 --> 00:44:09.360
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:44:09.360 --> 00:44:12.110
A caveat on the
[INAUDIBLE] question is,

00:44:12.110 --> 00:44:14.840
you talked about the data and
then also bringing the people

00:44:14.840 --> 00:44:18.560
together to co--design,
so to speak,

00:44:18.560 --> 00:44:22.670
what it is that this actionable
empathy can look like.

00:44:22.670 --> 00:44:25.850
Any ideas on who those
organizations are?

00:44:25.850 --> 00:44:28.220
Because you say you basically
are a dot connector.

00:44:28.220 --> 00:44:29.750
So I'm wondering,
could you give us

00:44:29.750 --> 00:44:32.150
some insight into who
those organizations are

00:44:32.150 --> 00:44:35.107
and who are the people that
we should be working with?

00:44:35.107 --> 00:44:36.690
DERAY MCKESSON:
Here's the hard thing.

00:44:36.690 --> 00:44:38.130
And Sam will be around
afterwards, too,

00:44:38.130 --> 00:44:39.290
so we can talk about this.

00:44:39.290 --> 00:44:40.380
Sam, raise your hand.

00:44:40.380 --> 00:44:40.880
We love Sam.

00:44:40.880 --> 00:44:42.290
Sam is great.

00:44:42.290 --> 00:44:44.990
I met Sam on Twitter
actually in 2015.

00:44:44.990 --> 00:44:47.435
Sam literally tweeted, I want
to help out, or whatever.

00:44:47.435 --> 00:44:48.810
And I dinged him
my phone number.

00:44:48.810 --> 00:44:51.620
We had a great call, and I was
like, we should work together.

00:44:51.620 --> 00:44:53.250
We've been together
for a long time.

00:44:53.250 --> 00:44:57.830
But the hard part is that there
are two types of organizers.

00:44:57.830 --> 00:45:00.560
There's one set that really
wants to be the gatekeeper.

00:45:00.560 --> 00:45:02.820
So they want you to do
as much work as you do,

00:45:02.820 --> 00:45:05.090
as long as you keep
coming back to them.

00:45:05.090 --> 00:45:06.980
There's another set of
organizers that say,

00:45:06.980 --> 00:45:09.750
we want to give you the tools
for you to go do the thing.

00:45:09.750 --> 00:45:11.810
There are way more of the
former than the latter.

00:45:11.810 --> 00:45:14.330
So some of the biggest
organizations doing good work

00:45:14.330 --> 00:45:16.400
in this space
don't actually want

00:45:16.400 --> 00:45:19.220
you to do anything that
is not the stuff that they

00:45:19.220 --> 00:45:20.430
tell you to do.

00:45:20.430 --> 00:45:22.000
And that's one of
the hardest pieces,

00:45:22.000 --> 00:45:24.320
is that there aren't good
models of organization

00:45:24.320 --> 00:45:28.010
to scale right now that could
take 2,000 volunteers, or 3,000

00:45:28.010 --> 00:45:30.620
volunteers, or are
frankly interested in you

00:45:30.620 --> 00:45:33.379
doing something that is
not at their direction.

00:45:33.379 --> 00:45:34.420
And that's the challenge.

00:45:34.420 --> 00:45:35.836
What we would say
is that we think

00:45:35.836 --> 00:45:39.721
that we can build something that
allows more people to plug-in

00:45:39.721 --> 00:45:40.970
and then go do your own thing.

00:45:40.970 --> 00:45:41.720
I don't care.

00:45:41.720 --> 00:45:42.710
If you want to--

00:45:42.710 --> 00:45:44.680
for example, there's
one company essentially,

00:45:44.680 --> 00:45:46.430
that when people get
released from prison,

00:45:46.430 --> 00:45:48.200
the money they have
on commissary gets

00:45:48.200 --> 00:45:49.890
put on a debit card--

00:45:49.890 --> 00:45:51.816
something like a debit card.

00:45:51.816 --> 00:45:53.690
It's a debit card that
every time you use it,

00:45:53.690 --> 00:45:55.070
it has a crazy transaction fee.

00:45:55.070 --> 00:45:56.310
It's a scam is what it is.

00:45:56.310 --> 00:45:57.685
AUDIENCE: It's
like the RushCard.

00:45:57.685 --> 00:46:00.000
DERAY MCKESSON: Yeah,
it's like-- ooooh.

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:00.780
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:00.780 --> 00:46:03.944
You're trying to get us in
trouble, talking about--

00:46:03.944 --> 00:46:05.360
it's something
like what you said.

00:46:05.360 --> 00:46:07.550
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:07.550 --> 00:46:09.980
But it's such a scam.

00:46:09.980 --> 00:46:13.340
What I believe is that
if we made that public--

00:46:13.340 --> 00:46:15.350
showed you every
place where that is--

00:46:15.350 --> 00:46:17.690
that if that was your
thing, you'd just go do it.

00:46:17.690 --> 00:46:19.710
You'd go dismantle it.

00:46:19.710 --> 00:46:21.830
If you need help,
cool, we'll be there.

00:46:21.830 --> 00:46:23.690
But you don't need me to.

00:46:23.690 --> 00:46:26.331
We did the first ever public
database of police [INAUDIBLE]

00:46:26.331 --> 00:46:28.580
in contracts and use of force
policies in the country,

00:46:28.580 --> 00:46:30.288
because nobody had
ever put them together

00:46:30.288 --> 00:46:31.460
so we did all this stuff.

00:46:31.460 --> 00:46:33.260
Because there's some
places where we go and they

00:46:33.260 --> 00:46:34.430
need our technical assistance.

00:46:34.430 --> 00:46:35.804
They need us to
come in and help,

00:46:35.804 --> 00:46:37.460
because we just
know the landscape.

00:46:37.460 --> 00:46:38.720
There's some places
that use the data

00:46:38.720 --> 00:46:39.790
and they just
fought on their own.

00:46:39.790 --> 00:46:40.665
And we're like, cool.

00:46:40.665 --> 00:46:42.380
As long as the outcome--

00:46:42.380 --> 00:46:44.570
we don't care.

00:46:44.570 --> 00:46:47.090
What we do know is we
know the big buckets

00:46:47.090 --> 00:46:49.502
of where the problems are.

00:46:49.502 --> 00:46:50.960
What we're trying
to figure out is,

00:46:50.960 --> 00:46:53.150
how do we get people
to help us find them?

00:46:53.150 --> 00:46:58.370
So when we coded the 100
police unit contracts

00:46:58.370 --> 00:47:01.130
in the 100 largest cities,
we had all these volunteers

00:47:01.130 --> 00:47:04.070
and Slack groups across the
country filling in Google Docs.

00:47:04.070 --> 00:47:05.840
We're about to code
800 more, so we

00:47:05.840 --> 00:47:09.560
have more volunteers helping us
sift through these contracts.

00:47:09.560 --> 00:47:14.900
We can do it in two weeks what
would take us two years to do.

00:47:14.900 --> 00:47:16.670
That's the interesting
scalable things.

00:47:16.670 --> 00:47:18.740
So there aren't great
models of it right now.

00:47:18.740 --> 00:47:21.350
And what you find is that a lot
of even the best organizations

00:47:21.350 --> 00:47:23.766
just don't-- they don't know
what they do with the dollars

00:47:23.766 --> 00:47:24.660
and the volunteers.

00:47:24.660 --> 00:47:25.910
They just don't right now.

00:47:25.910 --> 00:47:27.890
So we're trying to
help people envision

00:47:27.890 --> 00:47:30.646
organizing and being an activist
and a citizen differently.

00:47:30.646 --> 00:47:31.520
Does that make sense?

00:47:31.520 --> 00:47:31.570
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:47:31.570 --> 00:47:32.210
Yeah, yeah.

00:47:32.210 --> 00:47:33.918
I'm going to talk to
Sam afterwards, too.

00:47:33.918 --> 00:47:34.670
Thank you.

00:47:34.670 --> 00:47:35.290
DERAY MCKESSON: Sam is in.

00:47:35.290 --> 00:47:36.920
WILLIAM FLOYD: We have
time for one last question.

00:47:36.920 --> 00:47:38.320
AUDIENCE: Oh, a lot of pressure.

00:47:38.320 --> 00:47:39.530
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:39.530 --> 00:47:41.230
WILLIAM FLOYD: Make it good.

00:47:41.230 --> 00:47:43.760
AUDIENCE: So I've really enjoyed
everything that all of you

00:47:43.760 --> 00:47:44.959
have been speaking about.

00:47:44.959 --> 00:47:46.000
And thank you for coming.

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:48.540
Obviously, this has been
really, really helpful.

00:47:48.540 --> 00:47:50.520
My question is around allyship.

00:47:50.520 --> 00:47:55.010
So a lot of the things that
you're speaking around,

00:47:55.010 --> 00:47:57.560
a lot of times they come
off as minority problems,

00:47:57.560 --> 00:48:01.190
or black problems, or
problems that are focused

00:48:01.190 --> 00:48:03.630
on one specific community.

00:48:03.630 --> 00:48:05.789
But when I think back to
the Civil Rights movement,

00:48:05.789 --> 00:48:08.330
a lot of the people that were
in the crowd during the Freedom

00:48:08.330 --> 00:48:11.960
March, they were actually
people that were white.

00:48:11.960 --> 00:48:14.390
So when you think
about allyship,

00:48:14.390 --> 00:48:17.550
I would be curious to hear
what you think about that.

00:48:17.550 --> 00:48:20.130
And who are people that you
think are doing that well?

00:48:20.130 --> 00:48:22.460
And what's that call to
action look like for people

00:48:22.460 --> 00:48:23.984
that want to be allies?

00:48:23.984 --> 00:48:26.525
DERAY MCKESSON: So I think about
this big bucket is that when

00:48:26.525 --> 00:48:28.346
you think about allies
and accomplices--

00:48:28.346 --> 00:48:29.970
people's first
introduction to the work

00:48:29.970 --> 00:48:31.970
is almost always
being an ally and that

00:48:31.970 --> 00:48:33.440
is standing in solidarity.

00:48:33.440 --> 00:48:35.660
We think about
accomplices as people

00:48:35.660 --> 00:48:38.660
who see themselves
implicated in the work, too,

00:48:38.660 --> 00:48:40.700
who are not just people
standing near you,

00:48:40.700 --> 00:48:42.380
but standing side-by-side.

00:48:42.380 --> 00:48:46.600
Allies love you from a distance,
accomplices love you up close.

00:48:46.600 --> 00:48:49.856
A difference of proximity
is the difference here.

00:48:49.856 --> 00:48:51.480
I was talking to
somebody the other day

00:48:51.480 --> 00:48:53.060
who asked a similar question.

00:48:53.060 --> 00:48:55.050
We were just one-on-one.

00:48:55.050 --> 00:48:57.500
And he was like, I get
intersectionality--

00:48:57.500 --> 00:48:58.440
I get the idea.

00:48:58.440 --> 00:49:00.650
But he's like, I
often need to think

00:49:00.650 --> 00:49:03.392
about it in the frame of my
identity and I'm struggling.

00:49:03.392 --> 00:49:05.600
He's like, I'm not being
the best ally that I can be,

00:49:05.600 --> 00:49:07.292
so can we talk about it?

00:49:07.292 --> 00:49:09.250
What I said to him is
that people misunderstand

00:49:09.250 --> 00:49:12.590
intersectionality is about
being intersecting identities.

00:49:12.590 --> 00:49:15.640
And intersectionality is not
about intersecting identities.

00:49:15.640 --> 00:49:18.070
Intersectionality is
about intersecting sets

00:49:18.070 --> 00:49:19.840
of oppression.

00:49:19.840 --> 00:49:24.670
So being a black, gay man
is about how my gayness

00:49:24.670 --> 00:49:26.560
and being black intersect.

00:49:26.560 --> 00:49:28.460
It's not just about
how my identity

00:49:28.460 --> 00:49:30.066
has just all come together.

00:49:30.066 --> 00:49:32.440
It is rooted in the idea that
these systems of oppression

00:49:32.440 --> 00:49:33.164
intersect.

00:49:33.164 --> 00:49:34.330
And that's really important.

00:49:34.330 --> 00:49:36.663
And what I ask people now is,
when was the last time you

00:49:36.663 --> 00:49:38.080
didn't feel safe?

00:49:38.080 --> 00:49:40.090
And what's interesting
is that when

00:49:40.090 --> 00:49:41.950
I've asked white men
when the last time

00:49:41.950 --> 00:49:43.380
they didn't feel safe,
they say things like,

00:49:43.380 --> 00:49:43.960
when I didn't have money.

00:49:43.960 --> 00:49:45.400
And I'm like, that
is fascinating.

00:49:45.400 --> 00:49:46.976
[LAUGHTER]

00:49:46.976 --> 00:49:48.850
If that's the last time
you didn't feel safe,

00:49:48.850 --> 00:49:51.122
that is really interesting.

00:49:51.122 --> 00:49:53.080
And I asked a straight,
black man the other day

00:49:53.080 --> 00:49:54.639
when he didn't feel
safe, and he was

00:49:54.639 --> 00:49:56.680
like, the last time I
didn't feel safe in my body

00:49:56.680 --> 00:49:57.940
was around the police.

00:49:57.940 --> 00:50:01.450
And that's also interesting,
that the last time

00:50:01.450 --> 00:50:03.714
you didn't feel safe in
your body is around a--

00:50:03.714 --> 00:50:05.880
you ask a woman when the
last they didn't feel safe,

00:50:05.880 --> 00:50:07.870
it doesn't have anything
to do with the police.

00:50:07.870 --> 00:50:09.610
It might be about
the police, but women

00:50:09.610 --> 00:50:12.700
have all these stories about
not feeling safe in their body

00:50:12.700 --> 00:50:14.700
just in society.

00:50:14.700 --> 00:50:17.032
Or you ask queer
people, trans people,

00:50:17.032 --> 00:50:18.490
when's a time you
didn't feel safe,

00:50:18.490 --> 00:50:21.010
and you actually
understand what you

00:50:21.010 --> 00:50:23.230
don't see every day,
because you're just

00:50:23.230 --> 00:50:25.840
not proximate to it.

00:50:25.840 --> 00:50:28.060
I found that question to be
really helpful for people

00:50:28.060 --> 00:50:29.810
who are struggling
with this allied thing,

00:50:29.810 --> 00:50:33.140
like, how close are you to the
issue and what don't you see?

00:50:33.140 --> 00:50:34.330
Especially in the workplace.

00:50:34.330 --> 00:50:36.472
You think about
in classrooms-- we

00:50:36.472 --> 00:50:38.680
sit in the back of the
classroom and we can literally

00:50:38.680 --> 00:50:41.020
tally who gets called on.

00:50:41.020 --> 00:50:42.700
If you sit in
classrooms and you tally

00:50:42.700 --> 00:50:44.658
positive to negative
comments, you can actually

00:50:44.658 --> 00:50:46.210
learn a lot about a teacher.

00:50:46.210 --> 00:50:48.535
Because when you see the
ratio is just so off,

00:50:48.535 --> 00:50:50.410
you're like, of course
the kids are bad today

00:50:50.410 --> 00:50:51.530
because you're mean.

00:50:51.530 --> 00:50:55.990
That's why they're bad, because
you're not a nice person.

00:50:55.990 --> 00:50:57.550
But in the workplace
you can also

00:50:57.550 --> 00:50:59.500
tally who gets called on first.

00:50:59.500 --> 00:51:02.410
In a lot of workplaces that
call themselves progressive,

00:51:02.410 --> 00:51:06.100
it's always straight men who
are the first people to talk.

00:51:06.100 --> 00:51:07.390
What does that look like?

00:51:07.390 --> 00:51:09.796
I think, too, about workplaces
that look like this,

00:51:09.796 --> 00:51:11.170
it's like, what
does it mean when

00:51:11.170 --> 00:51:13.128
workplaces that look like
this say things like,

00:51:13.128 --> 00:51:14.410
we have the best workforce.

00:51:14.410 --> 00:51:17.230
And it's like, no black
people and no brown people.

00:51:17.230 --> 00:51:19.480
That is actually
signaling something.

00:51:19.480 --> 00:51:23.650
That if you can say today, you
have the best workforce when

00:51:23.650 --> 00:51:25.780
it's less than 3%
people of color,

00:51:25.780 --> 00:51:27.784
that is a value statement.

00:51:27.784 --> 00:51:29.200
And if you don't
see it like that,

00:51:29.200 --> 00:51:30.892
that is a privilege
and a luxury not

00:51:30.892 --> 00:51:32.350
to be able to see
the way that that

00:51:32.350 --> 00:51:33.972
is being received by people.

00:51:33.972 --> 00:51:36.430
Not that you're working towards
having the best work place.

00:51:36.430 --> 00:51:38.530
But if you would say that
the best workplace is

00:51:38.530 --> 00:51:40.570
one that does not
mimic a society

00:51:40.570 --> 00:51:43.200
we live in like this,
that is a real challenge.

00:51:43.200 --> 00:51:46.250
So I've seen people show
with the language of allyship

00:51:46.250 --> 00:51:48.992
and not the practice
of allyship a lot,

00:51:48.992 --> 00:51:50.200
and especially in workplaces.

00:51:50.200 --> 00:51:51.241
And what I've also seen--

00:51:51.241 --> 00:51:53.720
I did this talk at another
really big company.

00:51:53.720 --> 00:51:57.290
And I had gone to the airport
with the Vice President

00:51:57.290 --> 00:51:59.950
of whatever he does
at the big place.

00:51:59.950 --> 00:52:04.090
And he was the executive
sponsor for the black people.

00:52:04.090 --> 00:52:06.010
So I'm talking to the
black people later,

00:52:06.010 --> 00:52:06.880
and all they had was complaints.

00:52:06.880 --> 00:52:09.130
And I'm sitting up here and
I go to the executive guy.

00:52:09.130 --> 00:52:13.210
I'm like, you're not sponsoring
real well if the people got

00:52:13.210 --> 00:52:14.560
all these complaints.

00:52:14.560 --> 00:52:16.150
You are sponsoring
from a distance

00:52:16.150 --> 00:52:17.410
and that's just not cool.

00:52:17.410 --> 00:52:18.760
So you need to figure that out.

00:52:18.760 --> 00:52:20.500
And in workplaces
like this, is what

00:52:20.500 --> 00:52:22.660
you often find is that
there's a lot of really

00:52:22.660 --> 00:52:25.180
good systemic work happening
until one white person feels

00:52:25.180 --> 00:52:29.316
uncomfortable, and
people are like, no.

00:52:29.316 --> 00:52:30.940
It could be 30 black
people being like,

00:52:30.940 --> 00:52:33.430
I think this is
an issue that we--

00:52:33.430 --> 00:52:37.090
and the one white person
who has a fragile moment

00:52:37.090 --> 00:52:39.370
can shut everything down.

00:52:39.370 --> 00:52:43.480
When a structure allows that
to happen, that is a conver--

00:52:43.480 --> 00:52:45.332
we need to talk about that.

00:52:45.332 --> 00:52:47.290
And I think about that
with the allyship piece,

00:52:47.290 --> 00:52:49.600
is that I've seen people
in positions of power.

00:52:49.600 --> 00:52:51.554
Again, they will
come to something

00:52:51.554 --> 00:52:53.470
like this talk with me
and talk about the fact

00:52:53.470 --> 00:52:55.390
that they were here for
the next three months

00:52:55.390 --> 00:52:58.210
and not change any practice
that they've ever done.

00:52:58.210 --> 00:53:00.862
And I get that and
that's not cool.

00:53:00.862 --> 00:53:02.320
So we need to figure
out, how do we

00:53:02.320 --> 00:53:06.150
make spaces where we can
challenge systems internally

00:53:06.150 --> 00:53:08.770
so that they don't reproduce
the same sort of things

00:53:08.770 --> 00:53:13.300
that cause us to have these
talks in the first place?

00:53:13.300 --> 00:53:15.370
I'm more nervous
about that four years

00:53:15.370 --> 00:53:18.130
after the protests began
than I was at the beginning.

00:53:18.130 --> 00:53:20.620
We've been to a million talks,
a million of all this stuff.

00:53:20.620 --> 00:53:22.332
You've been to it,
I've been to it.

00:53:22.332 --> 00:53:24.040
And some people actually
haven't changed.

00:53:24.040 --> 00:53:26.620
And I do think the confrontation
and the challenging

00:53:26.620 --> 00:53:29.615
of those people has to be
front and center in this work.

00:53:29.615 --> 00:53:30.990
We're you about
to say something?

00:53:30.990 --> 00:53:31.300
AUDIENCE: No.

00:53:31.300 --> 00:53:32.150
DERAY MCKESSON: OK.

00:53:32.150 --> 00:53:34.920
And the last thing I
would say is this thing

00:53:34.920 --> 00:53:38.210
that we call caretaking--

00:53:38.210 --> 00:53:40.360
caretaking and splitting
are two different things.

00:53:40.360 --> 00:53:41.943
What you find with
some white people--

00:53:41.943 --> 00:53:43.150
and black people do it--

00:53:43.150 --> 00:53:45.051
is that a white
person has a moment--

00:53:45.051 --> 00:53:47.050
they're like, oh, my god,
I get white privilege.

00:53:47.050 --> 00:53:47.710
I get it.

00:53:47.710 --> 00:53:48.949
This is bad.

00:53:48.949 --> 00:53:50.740
Then they split from
the other white people

00:53:50.740 --> 00:53:52.392
and they go near
people of color.

00:53:52.392 --> 00:53:54.100
They're like, you
white people are crazy,

00:53:54.100 --> 00:53:56.141
we're going to go hang
out with the black people.

00:53:56.141 --> 00:53:59.110
And that feels like the right
thing to do in those moments.

00:53:59.110 --> 00:54:01.290
But the danger of splitting
is that-- white people,

00:54:01.290 --> 00:54:03.540
you need to go-- you need
to be with the white people.

00:54:03.540 --> 00:54:05.510
You need to be teaching
the white people,

00:54:05.510 --> 00:54:06.860
they've got to get
their stuff together.

00:54:06.860 --> 00:54:09.026
And white people have to
start leading white people.

00:54:09.026 --> 00:54:10.430
So it's not that
you shouldn't be

00:54:10.430 --> 00:54:11.638
proximate to people of color.

00:54:11.638 --> 00:54:12.230
You should be.

00:54:12.230 --> 00:54:16.490
But you shouldn't split
holy and use your proximity

00:54:16.490 --> 00:54:19.420
to black people as a
sense of credentialing.

00:54:19.420 --> 00:54:22.165
Because that actually doesn't
push us forward in the work.

00:54:22.165 --> 00:54:23.540
And the second
thing that happens

00:54:23.540 --> 00:54:26.964
that we call this sense
of caretaking is that--

00:54:26.964 --> 00:54:28.380
people of color,
you've definitely

00:54:28.380 --> 00:54:30.921
experienced this-- you'll be in
a room, you'll say something,

00:54:30.921 --> 00:54:32.037
people will say nothing.

00:54:32.037 --> 00:54:32.870
They'll be like, OK.

00:54:32.870 --> 00:54:34.560
A white person says the same
thing and people are like,

00:54:34.560 --> 00:54:35.360
great idea.

00:54:35.360 --> 00:54:37.610
And you're like,
what just happened?

00:54:37.610 --> 00:54:40.067
And what you find is
that people will coddle

00:54:40.067 --> 00:54:41.900
the white per-- they'll
be like, oh, my god,

00:54:41.900 --> 00:54:43.159
that was such an insight.

00:54:43.159 --> 00:54:45.200
That thing about race that
you said was so great.

00:54:45.200 --> 00:54:46.991
And you're like, I
literally just said that

00:54:46.991 --> 00:54:48.620
and that's my life all day.

00:54:48.620 --> 00:54:52.460
We need to be mindful that
white people's discomfort is

00:54:52.460 --> 00:54:55.279
because they are just realizing
what's happening in the world

00:54:55.279 --> 00:54:57.320
and that we shouldn't
coddle people through that.

00:54:57.320 --> 00:55:00.050
We should be around
them and support people,

00:55:00.050 --> 00:55:01.580
but that is not coddling.

00:55:01.580 --> 00:55:04.000
And a lot of what we do
know is coddle people.

00:55:04.000 --> 00:55:06.260
And that white privilege
is really important only

00:55:06.260 --> 00:55:09.119
insofar as people link that
back to a systemic factor.

00:55:09.119 --> 00:55:10.910
So if your understanding
of white privilege

00:55:10.910 --> 00:55:13.749
is limited to, oh, the
world is crazy and whatever,

00:55:13.749 --> 00:55:15.540
and you've not yet done
the work to realize

00:55:15.540 --> 00:55:17.960
that a system allowed
that to happen for you,

00:55:17.960 --> 00:55:20.500
then you actually haven't
done the work yet.

00:55:20.500 --> 00:55:23.360
And that is a long
answer to this question

00:55:23.360 --> 00:55:25.530
of what allyship looks like.

00:55:25.530 --> 00:55:27.132
[LAUGHTER]

00:55:27.132 --> 00:55:28.340
BONITA STEWART: But a great--

00:55:28.340 --> 00:55:29.173
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:55:29.173 --> 00:55:31.276
BONITA STEWART: --question
and a great answer.

00:55:31.276 --> 00:55:32.150
DERAY MCKESSON: Cool.

00:55:32.150 --> 00:55:32.810
It's good to be here.

00:55:32.810 --> 00:55:34.430
My book comes out
in September, it's

00:55:34.430 --> 00:55:36.013
called "On the Other
Side of Freedom."

00:55:36.013 --> 00:55:38.140
[APPLAUSE]

00:55:38.140 --> 00:55:40.241
Excited about that.

00:55:40.241 --> 00:55:42.210
And please listen to the pod--

00:55:42.210 --> 00:55:43.380
Sam will be here, too.

00:55:43.380 --> 00:55:44.380
I'd love to talk to
whoever's around.

00:55:44.380 --> 00:55:45.910
We are trying to
figure out, how do

00:55:45.910 --> 00:55:49.630
we create just more
space so people can have

00:55:49.630 --> 00:55:51.610
less gatekeepers in the work?

00:55:51.610 --> 00:55:53.470
You should be able
to do good work

00:55:53.470 --> 00:55:55.610
and not have to be a
member of anything,

00:55:55.610 --> 00:55:57.362
not have to join a network.

00:55:57.362 --> 00:55:59.320
You should be able to do
good work because work

00:55:59.320 --> 00:56:03.100
is good to do, not because
you want to join something

00:56:03.100 --> 00:56:04.480
for your whole life.

00:56:04.480 --> 00:56:06.080
How do we use tech
to allow people

00:56:06.080 --> 00:56:08.754
to do that is a question
that we have every day.

00:56:08.754 --> 00:56:09.670
BONITA STEWART: Great.

00:56:09.670 --> 00:56:10.710
WILLIAM FLOYD: We'd like
to help you answer that.

00:56:10.710 --> 00:56:12.130
DeRay, thank you for the time.

00:56:12.130 --> 00:56:13.213
BONITA STEWART: Thank you.

00:56:13.213 --> 00:56:16.080
[APPLAUSE]

